    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Votes B: our terms throughout, only 德 gets the split",
    "content": "**B.** Use our dictionary terms throughout, including in the block quote. Only 德 gets the split treatment.\n\nThe reason is structural: 德 is the term the author *reinterprets*. The shift from \"virtue\" to \"character\" marks a genuine conceptual departure that the reader should feel. But 仁, 义, and 礼 are not reinterpreted in the same way -- the author distinguishes 现象仁 from theoretical 仁, but does not argue that 仁 means something fundamentally different from \"humaneness.\" The standard translations (\"benevolence,\" \"righteousness,\" \"rites\") are not *wrong* for the author's usage -- they are just less precise than our dictionary choices.\n\nSplitting all five terms would create a confusing cascade of terminological switches in a single passage. The reader would encounter \"benevolence\" in the quote and then \"humaneness\" two sentences later for the same character, with no philosophical reason for the change -- just translator preference. That is noise, not signal.\n\nThe 德 split works because it *means* something. Extending it to 仁/义/礼 dilutes that signal."
  }
}
